<H3> <TI>   Government To Require Visas for UN Personnel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Require Visas for UN Personnel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304172494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1646 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 13 Apr (TANJUG) -- At this evening's 
session, presided over by Prime Minister Radoje Kontic, the 
federal government considered current questions of cooperation 
with the UN peacekeeping forces and decided that prior 
permission of the Yugoslav Government is necessary for the entry 
and movement of UN Protection Forces' [UNPROFOR] vehicles on the 
territory of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia [FRY]. Visas 
from the competent Yugoslav authorities will also be necessary, 
from 20 April, for the entry and residence of every member of 
the "Blue Helmets" in the FRY, the Federal Information Ministry 
has announced. 
  The federal government assessed that the UN peacekeeping 
forces, with their invitation to NATO to bomb Serb positions 
around Gorazde, have completely sided with the Muslim side in 
the civil war in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, and ignored the 
vital fact that it was precisely the Muslim forces, exploiting 
the safe zone, which attacked Serb positions first. 
  The federal government stated these facts with regret and 
once again condemned in the sharpest terms this behavior by 
UNPROFOR and the armed action of NATO. In the assessment of the 
federal government, these acts directly threaten the peace 
process and could lead to the escalation of the conflict, not 
only in this area but in a broader region. 
  In its cooperation with UNPROFOR hitherto, the Yugoslav 
Govenment was guided by its interest in the cessation of combat 
operations as soon as possible and in the reaching of a just 
solution through negotiations. It worked to the best of its 
ability and within its limited capabilities, to make it easier 
for UNPROFOR to perform its functions. The federal government 
did this, it was concluded, with huge sacrifices and efforts 
under the conditions of the unjustly imposed UN Security Council 
sanctions against the FRY, which contravene the UN Charter. 
  The Federal Ministry of Foreign Affairs has been tasked with 
informing the UNPROFOR main headquarters about the conclusions 
of the federal government, a statement by the Federal Ministry 
of Information says in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

