<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Proposes Changes to Air Defense System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Proposes Changes to Air Defense System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304124094 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 5 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "(km)": "Ground-Air Missiles To Be Put To Rest"] </F>
  [Text] The Army Command has proposed to the government to 
abolish the ground-based air defense of Prague, Brno, and 
Ostrava by 1995, when the transformation of the armed forces is 
expected to be completed. 
  "The Army believes that it is inefficient to constantly keep 
the so-called positional defense of objects in a state of 
alert," Vladimir Novak, commander of the Air Defense Department 
said. "This is why the Army wants to replace this defense 
system with a concept that would include the defense of 
important regions. Important regions would be designated as 
such depending on where the threat would be coming from." 
  The air defense missiles deployed in the vicinity of Prague, 
Brno, and Ostrava, which can be immediately launched at any 
time, would not be in a state of combat alert in the future. 
The Defense Ministry proposes that the air defense emergency 
system should be secured only by communication troops and 
fighter aircraft troops. 
  Air defense missiles would be put in a state of alert only 
in 
case of a military conflict. 
  Air defense is being secured by the Air Defense Brigade and 
the Air Defense Regiment--the exact deployment of which the Army 
declined to reveal--communication troops, and other units. An 
elite fighter aircraft regiment is in Ceske Budejovice, an 
independent fighter aircraft troop in Prerov, and a 
communication brigade in Klecany. The Air Defense Command is 
based in Stara Boleslav. 
  The first stage of air defense transformation began this 
year 
and will continue in the next year. Another two stages are 
planned for 1996 to 2000, and 2001 to 2005. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8508 </DOCNO>
