Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stresses Need for Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stresses Need for Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304161594 Paris AFP in English 1558 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 13 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serbs and 
Moslems have agreed to a ceasefire around the Moslem enclave of 
Gorazde, Russian special envoy Vitaliy Churkin said Wednesday 
[13 April]. 
  According to the Bosnian Serb SRNA news agency, Churkin said 
after a meeting with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic at his 
Pale headquarters that the "accord should help lead to a general 
ceasefire between Moslems and Serbs." 
  "I received assurances from the Serb and Moslem parties that 
they did not intend to engage in offensive acts in the Gorazde 
region, where the situation seems to be calm at the moment," he 
said. 
  "I think what we have achieved in Sarajevo and what we hope 
to achieve in Gorazde must be applied across the whole of 
Bosnia," he said, declining to say whether an actual ceasefire 
document had been signed. 
  Churkin, the personal envoy of Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin, has been mediating between the Bosnian Serb and Moslem 
factions and the UN Protection Force since Tuesday [12 April]. 
He had earlier met Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic. 
  The latest crisis in Bosnia, sparked by a Bosnian Serb 
offensive on Gorazde, was heightened at the weekend when North 
Atlantic Treaty Organization aircraft launched two air strikes 
against the besieging forces. 
  Churkin added: "All the parties to the conflict must 
understand that political accords about Gorazde cannot be 
implemented without their cooperation with the international 
community and among themselves." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

