<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Report Muslim Attacks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Report Muslim Attacks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304143194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1306 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1304143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Bratunac, April 13 (TANJUG)--Moslem forces from 
Gorazde on Wednesday continued artillery and infantry attacks on 
Bosnian Serb Army positions, the military sources of the army of 
the Bosnian Serb Republic (RS) have said. 
  The U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) commander for Bosnia, 
British General Michael Rose, on Tuesday said that the Gorazde 
Moslems are continuing unprovoked attacks on the Bosnian Serb 
army. 
  U.S. NATO jets on April 10-11 bombed Bosnian Serb positions 
near Gorazde, a U.N.-designated safe area which should have been 
demilitarized. 
  Instead, this Moslem enclave served as the startingpoint for 
a 10,000-strong Moslem offensive on Serb territories in late 
March. 
  At the same time, in northern Bosnia seven civilians were on 
Wednesday wounded seriously and four only slightly in a Moslem 
mortar attack on the city of Doboj, the Bosnian Serb military 
sources said. 
  The Moslems mounted artillery and mortar attacks on the 
Bosnian Serb army in the region of Mount Ozren, close to 
Gradiska, Orasje and Novigrad (northern Bosnia), Srbobran and 
Olovo (central Bosnia), Bihac (western Bosnia) and in the region 
of Mt. Majevica (northeast Bosnia). 
  In the Sarajevo area, the Bosnian Serb army repelled a 
strong 
Moslem infantry attack, while infantry fire was opened from the 
Moslem-controlled part of Sarajevo on the Serb parts of the 
city, it is said. 
  All these attacks are a part of a Moslem offensive on almost 
all parts of RS with the aim of seizing as much as possible 
territories before a final political solution is reached. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

