<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seselj: NATO Has Sided With Muslims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seselj: NATO Has Sided With Muslims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304171194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1611 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304171194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 13 Apr (TANJUG) -- Following his tour 
yesterday of the Bosnian Serb Army positions on the Gorazde 
battlefront and areas devastated by NATO air strikes, Vojislav 
Seselj, chairman of the Serbian Radical Party, met with Serb 
President Radovan Karadzic in Pale this afternoon. 
  Following that meeting, Seselj told journalists that NATO 
air 
strikes against Serb positions have greatly complicated the 
situation on the territory of former Bosnia-Herzegovina, since 
the air strikes against Serb positions mean NATO has sided with 
the Muslims. 
  The leader of the Serbian Radical Party added that this made 
NATO one of the warring sides, and as a result, it will have to 
bear all the consequences. The United Nations, by siding with 
the Muslims, has also lost its elementary objectivity. 
  "They can no longer be mediators in this conflict. In this 
way they have lost a lot -- not the Serbs. The morale of the 
Serb fighters, in my opinion, has never been better than now," 
Seselj stressed. 
  He added these air strikes have shown the war cannot be won 
from the air and that the Serbs cannot be defeated in this way. 

</TEXT>

