Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Officials Said Planning Fresh Attacks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Officials Said Planning Fresh Attacks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304152094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1459 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1304152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 13 (TANJUG) -- Following a Gorazde 
attack, NATO had already made plans to attack Bosnian Serb 
command posts, bridges on the Drina (eastern Bosnia), supply 
routes and even Pale, the administrative centre of the Bosnian 
Serb republic (S.R.), said Obrad Kesic, an expert on Balkan 
policy, who is close to Washington circles. 
  Speaking for the Belgrade evening paper VECERNJE NOVOSTI on 
Wednesday, Kesic said that a very powerful group of anti-Serb 
inclined Washington officials, having realized that Washington's 
peace initiative for Bosnia-Herzegovina had collapsed and 
fearing the reaction of the public opinion and media, were 
plotting to continue the aggression against the Bosnian Serbs. 
  He said that the group, which had already made plans of 
attacks on Bosnian Serbs, was headed by Anthony Lake, President 
Clinton's national security advisor, and added that it was 
especially influenced by Madeleine Albright, the U.S. ambassador 
to the United Nations. 
  Kesic said that the world power wielders had gone so far now 
that they had to launch airstrikes to prove their effectiveness. 
They were now, however, trying to find a way out of the 
horrible situation they had created themselves, knowing that if 
they backed up now the media would tear them apart. Kesic said 
that a continued aggression against the Serbs was very likely, 
which is supported by the fact that plans to that effect had 
already been made. 
  The bombardment of Bosnian Serb positions around Gorazde is 
a 
hot issue in Washington because the U.S. public initially backs 
U.S. military actions, but as soon as problems arise, it turns 
to fierce criticisms, Kesic said in conclusion. 
  U.N.-sponsored American warplanes within 24 hours (on Sunday 
and Monday) launched two air raids on Bosnian Serb positions 
around Gorazde (a Moslem enclave in eastern Bosnia), just as the 
Serb forces were about to crush a Moslem offensive, launched 
from Gorazde, a U.N.-designated "safe area", which should have 
been demilitarized back in 1993. 
  The anti-Serb lobby in Washington is preparing fresh attacks 
on the Bosnian Serb republic because it has realized that, after 
the failure of the U.S. peace initiative, Russia would become 
more engaged in helping settle the Yugoslav crisis and Europe 
would urge that the peace initiative for the former Yugoslavia 
be returned to Geneva. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8523 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu072_i_94019" </HT>


