<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkish Ambassador Views Deployment of Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turkish Ambassador Views Deployment of Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1404160494 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1404160494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Republic of Turkey is the first country to open 
an embassy in the capital of Bosnia-Herzegovina. At today's 
modest ceremony, Sukru Tufan, Turkish ambassador to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, unveiled the sign on the embassy building, 
thus officially opening the embassy and marking the beginning of 
its work. 
  Ambassador Tufan spoke about the friendly attitude of his 
country toward Bosnia-Herzegovina and the insistence of Ankara 
on the implementation of all the UN Security Council resolutions 
concerning Bosnia-Herzegovina. By sending in its armed forces, 
Turkey will be directly participating in the establishment of 
peace in our country. It is obliged to do so by both the deep 
roots and the links between our cultures and traditions. Thus 
the link between these two friendly and close countries is 
natural. 
  Turkey will continue to (rally) all the international forces 
in order to reach a just settlement to the crisis in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina as soon as possible, Ambassador Tufan said. 
  Another ceremony will be held this afternoon to mark the 
opening of the Turkish embassy in Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

