<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK President Against UN Deployment on Border </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RSK President Against UN Deployment on Border </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304133494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1144 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knin, 13 Apr (TANJUG) -- Milan Martic, the president 
of the republic of Serb Krajina [RSK], sent a letter today to 
UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] Commander General Bertrand de 
Lapresle expressing his surprise after being informed of 
UNPROFOR's intentions to deploy UN troops along the state border 
between the RSK and the Autonomous Province of Western Bosnia 
[APWB]. 
  Such a deployment, Martic says in his letter, is absolutely 
unacceptable and out of the question for us. The same goes for 
other RSK borders except those along demarcation lines with the 
Republic of Croatia, in accordance with the Zagreb agreement. 
  Reminding UNPROFOR Commander de Lapresle that he was one of 
the signatories of the Zagreb cease-fire agreement, in his 
letter Martic also points out: The governments of the RSK and 
the APWB have signed an agreement on friendship and cooperation; 
there have been no incidents in the border area and there is no 
need for your presence in this area, Martic says in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

