<HT>    "dreeu072_k_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-072 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Talks With Papoulias </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Talks With Papoulias </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304212394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2000 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and 
minister of foreign affairs, has returned to Zagreb following a 
visit to Greece today and Turkey yesterday. In Athens he had 
talks with Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias. After the 
talks both ministers concluded that it is possible to extend 
cooperation between the two countries. Andjelko Perincic 
reports on Minister Granic's visit to Athens: 
  [Perincic] Ministers Granic and Papoulias agreed that 
interstate treaties on industry, traffic, protection of 
investments, and the prevention of double taxation would soon be 
signed, and that business transactions should begin immediately. 
  At the meeting the two delegations also discussed military 
cooperation, Croatian-Greek cooperation in the sphere of 
security in southeast Europe and in the Mediterranean, and 
international military cooperation within the United Nations. 
Croatia obtained Greek support for its admission to NATO's 
Partnership for Peace. In this regard, Greece wants the same 
kind of friendship with Croatia as with all other countries of 
former Yugoslavia, it was said. 
  The Greek hosts also supported Croatia's efforts to 
reintegrate occupied Croatian areas in a peaceful way, adding, 
as Minister Papoulias himself stated at a news conference, that 
peace in that area and in Bosnia-Herzegovina would be a basis 
for peace in the entire region. Papoulias said that fighting 
should be halted in Bosnia-Herzegovina, which is endangering 
peace processes, and that negotiations in which Serbs should 
also be included ought to be initiated. 
  As regards Bosnia-Herzegovina, Minister Granic stated for 
Croatian Radio: 
  [Begin Granic recording] Our joint conclusion is that a 
cease-fire agreement, and after that, the inclusion of the third 
party, the Serb party, into negotiations with the federation [of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina] are the most important things at the moment. 
Greece ought to take an even more active part, as the European 
Union [EU] chairman, in the peace process, the process of 
negotiations, together with the United States and the Russian 
Federation. [end recording] 
  [Perincic] The talks in Athens were also useful because 
Greece is currently the EU chairman. Therefore, its support for 
Croatia to join the EU PHARE [Economic Reconstruction Aid for 
Poland and Hungary] program is not insignificant. Greece lends 
its support to Croatia for other forms of cooperation with the 
European Union and for our efforts to obtain aid from the IMF, 
the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, and other 
international financial institutions for the reconstruction of 
our country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

