<F P=101> Albania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Asks UNSC To `Condemn' Greece </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Asks UNSC To `Condemn' Greece </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1404085294 Tirana ATA in English 0814 GMT 14 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1404085294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Albania Asks the UN Security Council To Condemn Greece" -- </F>
ATA headline] 
  [Text] Tirana, April 14, (ATA) -- Albania asked the UN 
Security Council [UNSC] to condemn Greece for the Sunday attack 
by "Greek terroristic commandos" against a military training 
centre of the Albanian Army in the Peshkepi village, near the 
border with Greece. As is known, an Albanian officer and one 
soldier were killed. 
  In a letter to the president of the UN Security Council, Mr. 
Colin Keating, on Tuesday, the Albanian foreign minister, Alfred 
Serreqi pointed out that the incident is "a grave terroristic 
act," "A massacre of the people while they were sleeping," and 
"a serious violation of the territorial integrity and 
sovereignty of Albania with clear and premeditated aims." This 
act aims not only at deteriorating the present relations between 
the two countries but also to the aggravation of the situation 
in the Balkans, the letter says. It is part of a coordinate 
strategy, in order to create premises for the expansion of the 
conflict in the south of the Balkans." 
  The Government of the Republic of Albania asks the Security 
Council to denounce powerfully the Greek Government and to rank 
Greece among the countries that exercise state terror, and to 
make pressure on the Government of Greece, demanding it to throw 
light on this grave incident, to find out and punish the authors 
of the crime. 
  On wednesday, the Albanian Foreign Ministry declared 
"persona 
non grata" the Greek general consul in Gjirokaster "because of 
his activity not in accordance with his status." In revenge for 
this act, the Greek Government adopted the same measure against 
the first secretary ofthe Albanian Embassy in Athens, Kastriot 
Robo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

