<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister on NATO `Aggression' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister on NATO `Aggression' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304131894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1238 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1304131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, April 13 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Defence 
Minister Pavle Bulatovic on Wednesday described NATO air strikes 
on Bosnian Serb positions as an act of aggression against the 
Serb people, which could have unconceivable consequences. 
  In a statement to the Yugoslav news agency TANJUG, Bulatovic 
said that the United Nations had sided with the Moslems and thus 
discredited its peacekeeping role and moral prestige. 
  No one may use "arms to deny anybody's right to defend 
themselves and the Serb people have a legitimate natural right 
to self-defence, guaranteed them by the U.N. Charter," he said. 
  The defence minister said that NATO bombing of Serb 
positions 
around Gorazde had hit "not only all the Serbs, but also the 
conscience of every man opting for peace and ending of the war 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina. [no closing quotation mark as received] 
  Said Bulatovic: If NATO's aim had been to persuade all 
warring sides to start negotiating it produced nothing but an 
exactly opposite effect -- it encouraged those favouring a war 
option, and worried those well aware that peace cannot be 
reached by the force of arms. 
  He went on to say that, after an impartial justice show, 
representing an act of aggression against the Serb people, which 
could bring about unforeseeable consequences, one should expect 
and hope that NATO would give up the law of the stronger and 
enable the warring sides to lay their arms and return to 
negotiating a peaceful settlement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

