<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Post in Tuzla Hit by Serb Artillery Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Post in Tuzla Hit by Serb Artillery Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1404124494 Paris AFP in English 1235 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1404124494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 14 (AFP) -- Serb forces shelled the 
airport and town of Tuzla in northern Bosnia Thursday after an 
observation post of a Nordic UN battalion there came under brief 
artillery attack, a United Nations spokesman said. 
  Eleven shells fell on the airport mid-morning and three fell 
on the market in Tuzla, said Major Dacre Holloway with the UN 
Protection Force. There were no injuries, Halloway said. 
  He said the Nordic UN troops' observation post was hit with 
artillery fire early Thursday but gave no other details. 
  Elsewhere Thursday, Serb forces seized 17 UN peacekeepers 
guarding a weapons stockpile at Cifluk, northwest of the capital 
Sarajevo and just inside the heavy weapons exclusion zone around 
the capital ordered by the UN in February. 
  Tuzla's airport, closed since the start of the conflict two 
years ago, was opened under the threat of NATO bombardment of 
Serb positions only last month, allowing UN relief flights to 
bring humanitarian aid to hard-hit northern and central Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8559 </DOCNO>
