<H3> <TI>   Colombian Foreign Minister Arrives on Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Colombian Foreign Minister Arrives on Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Zieleniec, Sanin Discuss `Drug Mafia' </H4>

<F P=102> AU1204193694 Prague CTK in English 1810 GMT 12 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 12 (CTK) -- Cooperation in fighting 
the drug mafia and drug terrorism was discussed by Czech Foreign 
Minister Josef Zieleniec and visiting Colombian Foreign Minister 
Nohemi Sanin Posada at their meeting today, the two ministers 
told journalists after the meeting. 
  The integration structures of Europe and America such as, 
for 
example, the Partnership for Peace project, the Organization of 
American States, NATO and the North American Free Trade 
Agreement (NAFTA) were also discussed, Posada said, adding that 
Columbia was interested in joining NAFTA. 
  The two ministers discussed bilateral Czech-Colombian 
relations. Posada mentioned the prospects of concluding mutual 
agreements, especially an agreement on investment protection. 
The necessity of strengthening concrete cooperation between the 
two countries' businessmen and cooperation in the cultural 
sphere was stressed. 
  At the end of their meeting Posada presented Zieleniec with 
Order of St. Charles, the civic distinction which the Colombian 
Foreign Ministry awards to foreigners contributing to the 
development of relations with Columbia. The decision to award 
it Zieleniec was made by Colombian President Cesar Gaviria 
Trujillo in late March. 
  In his Decree, Trujillo pointed to Zieleniec's contribution 
to pursuing the principles of international co-existence, mutual 
respect and solidarity between governments and nations and to 
the development of new relations of friendship and cooperation 
between the Czech Republic and Latin American countries, 
including Columbia. 

</TEXT>

