<H3> <TI>   Ministry on Gorazde, Poland's EU Application </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry on Gorazde, Poland's EU Application </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204164194 Budapest MTI in English 1304 GMT 12 Apr 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204164194 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 12 April (MTI) -- The Hungarian Foreign 
Ministry considers the immediate cessation of attacks against 
the civilian population of Gorazde, the prevention of conflict 
escalation, and the furtherance of the Bosnian peace process 
with the participation of all sides to be a prime necessity, 
Hungarian foreign affairs spokesman Janos Herman said at his 
customary press briefing in Budapest on Tuesday [12 April]. 
  Herman was evaluating the situation that has come about in 
the wake of the Serbian attack on Gorazde. 
  The Foreign Ministry is following the situation with 
particular attention. Its situational analysis starts out from 
the fact that the NATO action was carried out based on UN 
Security Council resolutions, and that the implementation of 
these is an obligation of the member-states. 
  In answer to another question, Herman welcomed the Polish 
government's submission of its official European Union [EU] 
membership request to the current presidency of the European 
Union on April 8, parallel to the Hungarian move. 
  Herman noted with satisfaction that these historical steps 
were prepared in close concert between the Hungarian and the 
Polish governments. 

</TEXT>

