<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Seeks Support for EU Application </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pawlak Seeks Support for EU Application </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304124594 Warsaw PAP in English 1151 GMT 13 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1304124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, April 13 -- Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
has asked the prime ministers of the countries of the "Twelve" 
to support Poland's efforts for a membership of the European 
Union [EU]. Pawlak conveyed respective letters to the 
ambassadors of the European Union states at a meeting in Warsaw 
on Wednesday. 
  Greek Ambassador Yeoryios Alexandropoulos said that it is 
not 
for the ambassadors to decide whether to accept Poland as a EU 
member but that they will give their full support to Poland's 
application for the membership. 
  Governmental commissioner for the European integration Jacek 
Saryusz-Wolski said after the meeting that the foreign ministers 
of the "Twelve" are to meet in Luxembourg on April 18 to decide, 
among other things, on the sending of the Polish application to 
the European Commission for examination. "Such a move will help 
begin negotiations on Poland's membership of the union," he 
added. 
  Saryusz-Wolski said he hopes that Poland should become a 
full 
member of the European Union in 1999. 

</TEXT>

