<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shadow Cabinet Attacks Government `Interference' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shadow Cabinet Attacks Government `Interference' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1504095594 Prague CTK in English 2013 GMT 14 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1504095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 14 (CTK) -- The International 
Monetary Fund's (IMF) approach towards ex-premier Vladimir 
Meciar's government was tougher than that towards the current 
cabinet of Jozef Moravcik, Sergej Kozlik, deputy chairman of the 
shadow cabinet of the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) 
and the Slovak National Party (SNS) told journalists today. 
  The current cabinet has included "their shoe sizes" in many 
economic accounts, he said. For the first quarter of this year 
personal consumption as well as investment grew, prices 
stabilized and gross domestic product also grew against the same 
period last year, he added. 
  Kozlik described as confrontational the program of 
Moravcik's 
government and asked whether the current premier who formed the 
government as a non-confrontational one, was not "under the 
pressure of an artificially created opposition." 
  Commenting on rumors about the possible withdrawal of 
further 
deputies from the HZDS deputies' group Kozlik said that he 
"could not see into deputies' mind." However, the deputies' 
group apart, the HZDS was the most stable political party in 
Slovakia, Kozlik said. 
  Spokesman for the shadow cabinet Ondrej Hanko attacked 
Moravcik's government for its interference in the media and for 
exerting pressure on it. SNS Chairman Jozef Prokes said with 
regard to the pro-Meciar daily REPUBLIKA published by the 
state-owned Slovak news Agency TA SR, that there should exist a 
daily criticizing the government no matter who published it. 
"Because there where no criticism exists, objectivity ends," he 
added. Asked by CTK whether the state should finance the 
publishing of REPUBLIKA Kozlik said: "It does not have to but it 
can." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

