<F P=101> The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Todorov Denies Existence of Macedonian Language </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Todorov Denies Existence of Macedonian Language </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1404191194 Sofia BTA in English 1817 GMT 14 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1404191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nikolay Koev: "Bulgarian Minister's Visit to </F>
Macedonia Ends With Scandal"] 
  [Text] Skopje, April 14 (BTA) -- The two-day official visit 
of Bulgarian Minister of Science and Education Marko Todorov to 
Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] 
was broken off yesterday [13 April]. 
  Having conferred with his Macedonian counterparts Selmani 
and 
Bajaldziev on April 12, at the end of his visit Todorov was to 
sign a protocol on cooperation between the similar ministries of 
the two countries. The document, coordinated in advance with 
Macedonian experts in Sofia, said that the protocol was to be 
signed in the official languages in Bulgaria and Macedonia. 
  Yesterday the Macedonian side demanded that this established 
wording in bilateral practice and documentation be substituted 
for "the Macedonian and Bulgarian languages." The Bulgarian 
side refused to sign the document which marked the end of the 
visit which also envisaged a meeting with Macedonian Prime 
Minister Branko Crvenkovski. 
  Returning to Sofia, Minister Marko Todorov made a statement 
for the media saying there is no Macedonian language. In his 
opinion, it will be a betrayal of the Bulgarian language to 
recognize Macedonian as a foreign language. "I maintain that 
the formulation which Bulgaria suggests, `the official languages 
of the two countries,' is flexible and acceptable enough as it 
places Bulgaria and Macedonia on an equal footing," he said. 
Mr. Todorov expects that the language problem will be settled 
by signing the governmental agreement on cooperation between 
Bulgaria and Macedonia in science, education and culture, and 
that this will help make an adequate political decision. In 
Minister Todorov's view, the differences are temporary and it is 
to the interest of both Bulgaria and Macedonia to maintain good 
relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

