<H3> <TI>   Germany's Kinkel Arrives, Meets Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Germany's Kinkel Arrives, Meets Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1504075694 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 0400 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1504075694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Klaus Kinkel, vice chancellor and foreign minister 
of Germany, arrived in Bulgaria on an official visit last night. 
  After official talks at the Foreign Ministry this morning, 
Kinkel will pay a call on National Assembly Chairman Aleksandur 
Yordanov and have meetings at the Council of Ministers. This 
afternoon he will be received by President Zhelyu Zhelev. 
  Upon his arrival, the German foreign minister particularly 
stressed that there are no problems in the relations between 
Bulgaria and Germany. Regarding the international topics to be 
discussed in his talks, he said that he would certainly be 
discussing the situation in former Yugoslavia and the Balkans as 
a whole. In addition, the situation in Russia would not be 
omitted in the talks. Kinkel supposed that other subjects would 
crop up in the course of the talks that would prevent them from 
becoming tedious. Perhaps one of the reasons is this: 
  [Begin Kinkel recording, in German fading into Bulgarian 
report] Bulgaria lies very close to my heart, Mr. Kinkel said. 
He added that he will try to help Bulgaria in solving its 
problems, both in terms of joining the EU and in connection with 
its contacts with NATO and its relations with the IMF. I am 
sure that Bulgaria can count on the German foreign minister, 
Kinkel declared on his arrival at Sofia Airport. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

