<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs: UN Withdrawal Cedes Positions to Muslims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs: UN Withdrawal Cedes Positions to Muslims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404185894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1816 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404185894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 14 Apr (TANJUG)--The Information Service 
of the Serb Republic Army's [VRS] main headquarters has said in 
a statement that UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] units deployed 
on Mt. Igman and Mt. Bjelasnica, after they had taken over VRS 
positions on the basis of the agreement of 30 July 1993, today 
withdrew to the area of Hrasnica and to Sarajevo airport as 
agreed upon between the so-called Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and 
the UNPROFOR command in Sarajevo. 
  The statement says that by withdrawing their units from 
these 
positions, UNPROFOR is enabling the Muslim forces that come from 
Sarajevo through a tunnel under the airport to attack VRS 
positions and Serb territory in Trnovo and on Rogoj, with the 
objective to link Gorazde and Sarajevo. 
  These offensive actions--as well as those already taken from 
various locations against the plateau of Nisici--are aiding the 
Muslim offensive aimed at breaking up and conquering the 
territory of Serb Sarajevo. 
  The actions coordinated between UNPROFOR and the so-called 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army are aimed at forcing an energetic 
response from the VRS in the Sarajevo area, which would then be 
used as a pretext for the use of NATO air force against the Serb 
artillery positions around Sarajevo, which have been grouped and 
placed under UNPROFOR control, the statement says. 

</TEXT>

