<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims Shelling Doboj; Inter-Muslim Clashes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims Shelling Doboj; Inter-Muslim Clashes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404210294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1940 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1404210294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Doboj, April 14 (TANJUG)--Bosnian Moslem forces on 
Thursday twice shelled the Serb-controlled town of Doboj in 
north-eastern Bosnia-Herzegovina. About twenty shells hit the 
town in this former Yugoslav republic but there have been no 
reports about possible casualties. 
  In the meantime, Moslem-controlled radio of the autonomous 
province of western Bosnia reported that eight soldiers of the 
Fifth Corps loyal to the Sarajevo authorities had been killed 
and 15 wounded during heavy inter-Moslem clashes in the Cazinska 
Krajina region in western Bosnia on Thursday morning. 
  The source also said that three soldiers of the autonomous 
province had been killed. 
  Fierce attacks, supported by artillery fire, launched 
against 
positions of units loyal to Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic 
continued in the area of Velika Kladusa and Cazin on Thursday 
afternoon, Moslem Radio-Sarajevo reported. Two people were 
killed and 25 wounded in the attacks according to the same 
source. 
  Autonomous province of western Bosnia forces are destroying 
everything in their way with multi-barrelled missile launchers 
Osa and Zolja, Radio Sarajevo said. The autonomous province was 
proclaimed last year by Moslems--followers of Fikret Abdic, who 
oppose Izetbegovic's war-mongering policy. 
  The command in Sarajevo admitted that about 500 troops had 
been killed and more than 2,000 wounded during the eight months 
of inter- Moslem clashes. The provincial army announces a 
counter-offensive to liberate Cazin, which is held by 
Izetbegovic's loyalist. 

</TEXT>

