<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Envoys, Churkin Meet With Karadzic in Pale </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Envoys, Churkin Meet With Karadzic in Pale </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1504142494 Paris AFP in English 1349 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1504142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 15 (AFP) -- UN envoy Yasushi Akashi 
and mediator Thorvald Stoltenberg met with Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic Friday, the first such meetings since NATO air 
strikes on Serb forces around Gorazde, the Serbs reported. 
  The Bosnian Serb news agency SRNA said Russian special envoy 
Vitaliy Churkin, who has been mediating between the Serbs and 
the United Nations, was also at the meeting in the Serb 
headquarters at Pale outside Sarajevo. 
  The talks came a week after the Bosnian Serbs announced they 
were suspending contacts with the UN Protection Force [UNPROFOR] 
in the wake of the NATO raids against Serbs beseiging the 
eastern Moslem enclave of Gorazde Sunday and Monday. 
  Since then Bosnian Serb harassment of UN forces has 
increased 
dramatically, with a large number of UN personnel held against 
their will in the exclusion zone around Sarajevo. 
  Churkin has been in Pale, east of Sarajevo, for several 
days, 
trying to mediate with the Bosnian Serbs. Karadzic was also 
accompanied at the talks by his deputies, Nikola Koljevic and 
Biljana Plavsic, 
  SRNA said the meeting in Pale was aimed at relaunching the 
Bosnian peace process, seriously jeapordized by events since the 
Gorazde air strikes. 
  Radio Sarajevo Friday reported renewed fighting overnight in 
the besieged enclave of Gorazde. The casualty toll in Gorazde 
has risen to 12 dead, including three children, and 49 injured 
in the last 24 hours, the radio said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

