<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK: Croat Proposal `Hardly Acceptable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RSK: Croat Proposal `Hardly Acceptable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404214494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1929 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404214494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 14 Apr (TANJUG)--The government of the 
Republic of Serb Krajina [RSK] has described the Croatian side's 
proposal regarding future talks on economic relations and 
traffic links as "hardly acceptable at this point". 
  According to ISKRA [Krajina Serb news agency], the 
government 
has prepared its platform--which will be presented to the 
assembly committees--based on the modified Article 20 of UN 
Security Council Resolution 820, which envisages export and 
import of goods from and into the RSK under the control of 
UNPROFOR's [UN Protection Forces] civilian services. 
  The possibility of providing water supplies for Zadar is 
envisaged as a gesture of good will, in exchange for parts for 
the hydroelectric dam in Obrovac. After that, other 
problems--particularly traffic problems--would be addressed. 
  With regard to the assembly's decision that the 
government--which is currently being reappointed--should not 
hold talks with the Croatian side, the government has decided to 
accept this decision, noting that, if necessary, it will send a 
delegation only with a written order from the president of the 
RSK and the president of the assembly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

