<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Lodges `Sharp Protest' With Italy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Lodges `Sharp Protest' With Italy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404164394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1546 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404164394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 14 Apr (TANJUG)--Ambassador Branko 
Brankovic summoned Italian Charge d'Affaires Laura Mirachian to 
the Yugoslav Ministry of Foreign Affairs today and lodged the 
Yugoslav Government's note of sharp protest over the use of 
Italian airports for NATO military actions against the Serb 
people in the Srpska republic. 
  According to the ministry's statement, Ambassador Brankovic 
stressed that Italy had thereby taken on itself responsibility 
for the risk of escalation of the war with unforeseeable 
consequences. NATO military operations on the very border of the 
FRY [Federal Republic of Yugoslavia] are a provocation against 
the FRY, a threat against its security, and pose a serious 
threat to peace and stability in the region. Taking part in a 
NATO military action, even under UN auspices, is contrary to the 
CSCE principles on the peaceful resolution of disputes, the 
observance of which--as the CSCE chair country--Italy should 
particularly advocate. 
  Such actions by Italy are contrary to the efforts to achieve 
a just and lasting solution to the civil war in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and contradict principles of 
good-neighborliness and traditional cooperation between friendly 
countries and peoples. 
  The FRY Government--interested in preservation of peace and 
security in the region, in the fate of the Serbs, and in finding 
a peaceful and just solution for the civil war in the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina--expects the Italian Government to prevent 
any further use of its territory for armed actions against the 
Serbs in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

