<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Chief on `Consequences' of NATO Strikes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Chief on `Consequences' of NATO Strikes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404161794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1519 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 14 Apr (TANJUG)--In connection with the 
NATO air strikes against Serb targets around Gorazde, Colonel 
General Momcilo Perisic, chief of the general staff of the 
Yugoslav Army, has stated that "such NATO air force action can 
undeniably have unforeseeable consequences for peace in the 
Balkans and Europe." 
  In an interview to be published in the POLITIKA daily 
tomorrow, Gen. Perisic said that "in the case of further air 
strikes against Serb territories, there is a danger of an 
escalation of the war to an uncontrollable degree." 
  He said that "the NATO air strikes against Serb territories 
around Gorazde complicated the military and political situation 
in former Bosnia-Herzegovina", and that this action "encouraged 
the supporters of the war option and worried those who carry 
peace in their hearts." 
  "I particularly wish to stress that this is an act of 
aggression against the Serb people, who have a legitimate and 
natural right to self-defense guaranteed by the UN Charter." 
  The Yugoslav Army chief of staff stressed that "the Yugoslav 
Army has continuously and attentively been following 
developments after the NATO air strikes", and that it has been 
taking "all necessary measures for the protection of the 
territorial integrity of our country." 
  "In the case of a possible violation of the air space of the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, the army will take actions in 
accordance with the rules of its combat operations," Gen. 
Perisic said. 

</TEXT>

