<DOCNO> FBIS4-8637 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu073_y_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-073 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milosevic Meets With Karadzic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Milosevic Meets With Karadzic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404174694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1655 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 14 Apr (TANJUG) -- President of Serbia 
Slobodan Milosevic today received president of the Srpska 
republic Radovan Karadzic. They discussed the latest situation 
in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, including the attempts by 
international mediators and envoys to normalize the situation. 
  After the meeting, Karadzic said, in a brief statement to 
correspondents, that the international community is now most 
concerned by our break of relations with the United Nations. "We 
will see whether our supreme command will make any changes to 
that decision tomorrow," Karadzic added. 
  The Srpska republic president confirmed that tomorrow he 
will 
meet with Yasushi Akashi, the UN secretary general's special 
envoy, and that he will inform him about the supreme command's 
position, which determines whether there will be any contacts 
with the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] civilian section. 
  Karadzic also commented on the latest situation on the 
Bosnian front. According to him, the first day of good weather, 
which had enabled U.S. NATO planes to fly "was used by the 
Muslim forces to try to chase us away from the right bank of the 
Drina River. They launched a new offensive from the left bank, 
accross the bridges, against our forces. They probably expected 
support from U.S. planes," he added. As far as Doboj is 
concerned it was permanently shelled, and there are losses among 
civilians, Karadzic commented. 
  The Muslim offensive is now under way practically on all 
fronts -- near Kupres, Srbobran, and Teslic. The strongest is 
from Teocak and Zvornik, via Kladanj and Olovo, to Ilijas. It is 
an entirely Muslim offensive, Karadzic stressed. They pulled out 
about 20,000 soldiers from Sarajevo. They were under an 
obligation to keep these soldiers in Sarajevo, but they pulled 
them out and deployed them on other fronts. 
  As for Tuzla Airport, cargo planes have been landing there 
and delivering military equipment for days. "We warned them that 
the airport was not open and that it would be opened exclusively 
on the basis of our agreement with Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin, envoy Vitaliy Churkin and Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev," Karadzic said. 
  Before this is agreed, the airport must not be used for 
military purposes, but it must not be abused even after it is 
opened. The airport can be used exclusively for humanitarian 
purposes, the Srpska republic president stressed. "Two cargo 
planes were preparing to land at Tuzla Airport today and we 
warned them not to. I think this is better than shooting them 
down." 
  Dwelling on the latest Russian proposals, conveyed to 
President Milosevic and the Bosnian Serbs by Russian envoy 
Vitaliy Churkin, Karadzic confirmed that these proposals did 
exist and that they could help bring about an overall peace, but 
not a political solution at the same time. Only complete peace 
could possibly lead to the speedy attainment of a political 
solution. We will examine these proposals and we will see, 
Karadzic said. 
  He urged a full cessation of hostilities throughout the 
former Bosnia-Herzegovina, stressing that he is against "a 
partial cease-fire," because, as he said, "if they are attacking 
us in Olovo we will attack them in all other areas." "We have 
the right to conduct a defense and a counteroffensive in all 
areas." 
  "We believe that an agreement on the cessation of 
hostilities 
ought to be concluded, but it should be understood that the 
sanctions against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia are an act 
of hostility, and if the hostilities cease, then the sanctions 
should also be abolished," Karadzic concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

