<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milosevic Meets With Owen, Stoltenberg </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Milosevic Meets With Owen, Stoltenberg </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404193294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1857 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 14 Apr (TANJUG)--Serbian President 
Slobodan Milosevic received Thorvald Stoltenberg and Lord Owen, 
cochairmen of the Conference on the Former Yugoslavia, this 
evening. 
  The Serbian president and the Geneva conference cochairmen 
exchanged views on the latest situation in the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and other important issues related to a 
political resolution of the crisis. They particularly focused on 
initiatives and ideas linked to ending the armed confrontations 
and creating conditions to restore the negotiating process. 
  The Serbian president believes that an end to all 
hostilities 
in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina should be achieved, which 
means, first of all, that the Muslim forces should give up any 
further military provocation. The responsibility for their 
behavior rests to the greatest extent with the international 
community, which has not only tolerated but--by undertaking air 
attacks against the Serbs--also openly encouraged the Bosnian 
Muslim leadership to continue the war. 
  The success of the peace process depends directly on 
abandoning discriminatory practices and on returning to the 
international community's principles of impartiality and 
objectivity, Milosevic stressed in his talks with Stoltenberg 
and Owen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

