<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Comments on Talks With Milosevic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Comments on Talks With Milosevic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404193994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1834 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 14 Apr (TANJUG) -- Serbian President 
Slobodan Milosevic received Russian Special Envoy Vitaliy 
Churkin this evening for the third time in the last 24 hours. 
  Commenting on the three rounds of talks with Milosevic, 
which 
altogether lasted about five hours, Churkin told journalists he 
was satisfied with the talks, that they were constructive, and 
had focused mostly on the cessation of hostilities in the whole 
of former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  "I can say now, after the third round, that what I have in 
my 
hands now is a good basis for achieving an agreement on the 
cessation of hostilities in the whole of former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina," Churkin stressed. 
  The Russian envoy told journalists he was leaving for Pale 
and Sarajevo early tomorrow morning and that he would work very 
intensively on the realization of the agreement on the cessation 
of hostilities in former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  "My main objective is to end the current very difficult 
situation and to proceed toward the political resolution of the 
Bosnian crisis," Churkin said. 
  He refused to give any more details regarding the talks with 
President Milosevic, but expressed hope that the other (Muslim) 
side would show as constructive an approach as the Serb side. 
"In any case, I am awaiting the talks in Sarajevo tomorrow with 
hope," Churkin added. 
  Asked whether he was now, after the third round of talks 
with 
Milosevic, more optimistic then before the talks, he said: "I 
think we have done a good job and, with a bit of luck, we could 
change the situation in Bosnia." 

</TEXT>

