<H3> <TI>   Havel Spokesman on Expectations for Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Havel Spokesman on Expectations for Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1504100494 Prague CTK in English 2041 GMT 14 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1504100494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 14 (CTK) -- The question of the 
Temelin nuclear power station in south Bohemia should not 
provoke controversy between Czech President Vaclav Havel and 
Austrian President Thomas Klestil at the forthcoming meeting of 
seven Central European presidents in the east Bohemian town of 
Litomysl, Havel's spokesman Ladislav Spacek said today. 
  "It is impossible for the topic of Temelin not to appear at 
the meeting," Spacek told journalists. He added, however, that 
it was impossible to expect that the debate on the nuclear power 
plant would be conducted on "some specific level." The 
discussion will probably be on how to ensure nuclear security in 
Europe, Spacek said. 
  Klestil intends, during his meeting with Klaus on Friday [15 
April], to convince the Czech president of the necessity of new 
steps concerning the Temelin nuclear plant. In an interview 
with Green representatives in Vienna today Klestil promised that 
he would seek to table discussion on the ecological impact of 
the construction and would contribute to the renewal of talks on 
planning permission. 

</TEXT>

