<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa Opposes Attempts To Limit Powers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa Opposes Attempts To Limit Powers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604122294 Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network in 
Polish 1000 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1604122294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Relayed by Warsaw TV Polonia Network] </F>
  [Text] Commenting on the proposed amendments to the Small 
Constitution which would limit his powers, President Lech Walesa 
said that he would have to ask for greater control over what 
Sejm deputies are doing. 
  Lech Walesa, who is in Litomysl, said that he does not 
believe that the coalition has serious thoughts about limiting 
presidential rights, but if it makes such an attempt then it 
will bear the consequences. 
  Presidential Spokesman Andrzej Drzycimski stated that if 
amendments to the Constitution were passed in the Sejm, the 
president would then have to defend the Constitution. 
  A group of Polish Peasant Party [PSL] and Democratic Left 
Alliance [SLD] deputies who tabled the bill with these 
amendments want the Sejm to have the power to appoint 
ministerial candidates put forward by the prime minister, should 
the president refuse to sign such a nomination. According to 
the bill, the dissolved Sejm would end its term of office only 
on the day of the first sitting of a newly elected parliament. 
The coalition needs a two-thirds majority in the Sejm to pass 
the amendments to the Constitution. To achieve such a majority, 
the SLD and PSL deputies require a dozen or so votes more. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

