<DOCNO> FBIS4-8693 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu074_h_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   MDF Spokesman Cited on Foreign Policy Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MDF Spokesman Cited on Foreign Policy Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504132094 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1000 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Gyorgy Csoti, foreign affairs spokesman of the 
Hungarian Democratic Forum [MDF], has held a press briefing 
about the MDF's foreign policy views. Judit Laszlo supplies the 
details. 
  [Laszlo] The MDF welcomes the policy of Slovak Prime 
Minister 
Jozef Moravcik because his government is willing to hold a 
dialogue, Gyorgy Csoti, the party's foreign affairs spokesman, 
said when analyzing Hungarian-Slovak relations. In connection 
with the southern Slav crisis, Gyorgy Csoti said that the 
slowdown in negotiations is alarming. In his view, Russia and 
the West ought to coordinate their activity more closely to 
resolve the crisis. 
  The foreign affairs spokesman called attention to the 
dangerous phenomena of Hungarian party politics, particularly in 
connection with a statement made by Gyula Horn, chairman of the 
Hungarian Socialist Party [MSZP]. 
  Gyula Horn met with Romanian Senate President Oliviu Gherman 
yesterday and then told journalists that in the view of the MSZP 
an agreement is possible concerning the issue of a 
Hungarian-Romanian basic treaty. According to Gyorgy Csoti, 
this suggests that it is the fault of the current Hungarian 
Government that a basic treaty has not so far been signed and 
that an agreement would be possible if the MSZP came to power. 
  For this reason, the MDF, having drawn the general 
conclusions, is of the view that the Alliance of Free Democrats 
[SZDSZ] and the MSZP -- presumably in a coordinated manner -- 
are subordinating basic foreign political interests to party 
goals in the election campaign. This conduct seriously harms 
the country's security; it weakens our negotiating positions 
with Slovakia, Romania, and Serbia, and it makes a historical 
reconciliation with our neighbors impossible, the MDF statement 
points out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

